<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Overview:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
While <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>EverQuest</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> rightly emphasizes grouping, it is the case that many players depend on ability to solo adequately well in order to advance in the game with their available play time.  Players often chose classes in part because of their ability to solo.  With the advent of <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Planes of Power</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, mages from 61st to 64th level have had their ability to solo significantly diminished through a combination of hard hitting mobs and changes to the experience system.  The loss of an important game capability for mages is frustrating and reduces the enjoyment of the game.  As traditional soloing classes that kite and charm have retained their ability to solo, it is only fair that mages do too.<br>
<br>
The purpose of this thread is to explore and compare possible remedies.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Possible Remedies:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Just deal with it.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
With <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Luclin</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Planes of Power</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, mages have enjoyed a renaissance in power, and are greatly desired in groups because of their ability to deal sustained damage.  Mages should simply join groups, or find appropriate partners.  Pet and caster groups are viable, mages do well in traditional trinity groups, and new tactics may make soloing more viable as well.  Alternately, simply level to 65, get <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Call of the Archmage</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and start suckling on the teat of charm soloing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Decreased Elemental Vulnerability:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Mages cannot solo using their traditional methods of either chaining or sustaining pets because <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs tear through elementals like they were wet pinatas.  One solution is to greatly increase pet hits points or some form of damage mitigation.<br>
<br>
However, in order to be effective, it would have to be a dramatic change, on the order of doubling elemental hitpoints or its equivalent.  While this might allow mages to use pets to solo, it would make pets even more desirable as tanks in groups, and might reduce class inter-dependence to the detriment of melees.  However, if pet damage output remains the same then increasing pet hitpoints does not increase the rate at which pet groups kill mobs.  It would however reduce down time, perhaps greatly.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Allow Mages to Kite Effectively:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Kiting, that is killing a mob that is moving instead of meleeing, neatly sidesteps the problem of high damage output mobs.  Since mages lack snare, they cannot really kite.  Giving mages snare might be overpowering, but giving it to their post-50 fire pets might be a tenable solution, and might make those pets viable.  Alternately, some classes use <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Flash of Light</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> to kite, and mages might be able to use it that way.  It would also give mages a needed means of escape when caught with their pets down.<br>
<br>
However, this would dramaticly change the way mages fight.  The usual mage solo style involves chaining or sustaining pets in a static fight, and kiting would be a big change.  Also, mage kiting might turn out to be so much less effective than wizard or druiding kiting to the point where it does little to solve the problem.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Give Mages Better Damage Mitigation:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs hit so hard that slow is practically necessary.  Many have suggested giving mages a modest but significant slow through a summoned pet only weapon.  Alternately, the direct damage component of the post-50 earth elemental root could be replaced by an appropriate slow effect.<br>
<br>
However, slow is a powerful ability, and not thematicly consistant with the mage class.  Mage are already desirable for groups.<br>
<br>
Conceivably, epic and air elemental stun could be improved to the point of being comparable in effectiveness to slow, but a stun good enough to solo with this might be overpowering in groups.<br>
<br>
It has also been suggested elsewhere that mages get root.  However, this would be game altering if not overpowering, and would also give mages crowd control abilities they do not currently possess.  The lack of root, snare, etc., has long been considered a linch pin of mage class balance.  One is reluctant to fool with such.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Un-nerf post-60 Experience outside PoP:</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
The root of the problem is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Planes of Power</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->.  First, because the mobs hit so hard, and second, because pre-<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs green out so quickly that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is the only viable hunting grounds post-60.  If post-60 mages could effectively solo experience outside <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, then existing soloing methods and abilities would be sufficient.  This would also make more of the game world viable again.<br>
<br>
However, it is clear that post-60 experience was intended by the designers to be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> only.  Changing experience gain might have unintended consequences.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Summary:</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Because <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> mobs have high damage output, traditional methods of mage soloing break down.  It is difficult to propose a balanced solution that allows mages to effectively solo that does not over power them in groups.<br>
<br>
I welcome your thoughtful responses.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
